tly, we can express it using AND/OR operations directly from Karnaugh map. But the simplest approach is recognizing that this is an even parity checker which equals 1 if number of 1s is even.\\n\\nFor implementation, using the XOR operation directly is most efficient. Since it\'s a combinational circuit, I\'ll use an \'always @(*)\' block to compute the output based on the inputs.",\n    "module": "module TopModule (\\n    input a,\\n    input b,\\n    input c,\\n    input d,\\n    output q\\n);\\n\\n    // Even parity function - output is 1 if even number of inputs are 1\\n    always @(*) begin\\n        q = a ^ b ^ c ^ d;\\n    end\\n\\nendmodule"\n}')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nThe error below has been reported by the format tool:\n<format_error>\n{\n    "stdout": "",\n    "stderr": "./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard3_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob103_circuit2/rtl.sv:11: error: q is not a valid l-value in TopModule.\\n./output_t22c_qwen3coder30b_shard3_0/VERILOG_EVAL_V2_Prob103_circuit2/rtl.sv:6:      : q is declared here as wire.\\nElaboration failed\\n"\n}\n</format_error>\nTo understand the error message better, we offered a version of generated module with line number:\n<module_with_lineno>\n1: module TopModule (\n2:     input a,\n3:     input b,\n4:     input c,\n5:     input d,\n6:     output q\n7: );\n8: \n9:     // Even parity function - output is 1 if even number of inputs are 1\n10:     always @(*) begin\n11:         q = a ^ b ^ c ^ d;\n12:     end\n13: \n14: endmodule\n\n</module_with_lineno>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nYour response will be processed by a program, not human.\nSo, please STRICTLY FOLLOW the output format given as XML tag content below to generate a VALID JSON OBJECT:\n<output_format>\n{\n    "reasoning": "All reasoning steps and advices to avoid syntax error",\n    "m